      Oh Litecoin
   =20
 =20
One thing you can do is buy a bunch of stock in some small publicly traded =
company and then put out a fake press release saying that Walmart Inc. is g=
oing to acquire that company. The stock will go up and you can sell your st=
ock at a profit. Later Walmart and the company will deny it and the stock w=
ill go back down, but if you=E2=80=99re quick you can make a profit. Even l=
ater, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and federal prosecutors w=
ill come after you, but if you cover your tracks well and live in a foreign=
 country you might be okay. Anyway this is very much  a thing that people d=
o occasionally in the U.S. stock market.Another thing you can do is buy a b=
unch of some cryptocurrency and then put out a fake press release saying th=
at Walmart is going to  =E2=80=9Cpartner with=E2=80=9D that cryptocurrency:=
Walmart Inc. said it hasn=E2=80=99t agreed to partner with Litecoin, refuti=
ng a statement earlier Monday that sent the cryptocurrency soaring.=C2=A0Th=
e statement released by GlobeNewswire isn=E2=80=99t authentic, a Walmart re=
presentative confirmed to Bloomberg News. The company is in the process of =
trying to learn more about the release. The Litecoin Foundation said in a t=
weet that it hadn=E2=80=99t entered a partnership with Walmart.=C2=A0At 9:3=
0 a.m. in New York, GlobeNewswire issued a statement saying that the world=
=E2=80=99s largest retailer had agreed to partner with Litecoin and accept =
the cryptocurrency as payment. Litecoin had soared as much as 33% on the an=
nouncement, with other cryptocurrencies gaining as well. Litecoin erased al=
most all of its gain, rising less than 1% at 12:12 p.m. in New York. Walmar=
t shares fell less than 1% to $145.01 after earlier trading in positive ter=
ritory.=C2=A0A spokesperson for Intrado, which operates GlobeNewswire, said=
 the company is removing the release from its website and is investigating =
the incident. Intrado distributes 200,000 press releases per year, accordin=
g to its website.This is probably better than the corporate version, for al=
l the reasons that crypto is generally attractive for crime. You can trade =
your Litecoin anonymously, without going through a broker who will rat you =
out to the SEC. You can trade your Litecoin any time; you don=E2=80=99t hav=
e to wait for the markets to open to put out your press release. Also this =
will just=C2=A0work=C2=A0really well: =E2=80=9CWalmart buys small company=
=E2=80=9D is news, for the small company, but not that many people will car=
e; =E2=80=9CWalmart does crypto thing=E2=80=9D is going to get more attenti=
on, so people will definitely read your fake news and the price of Litecoin=
 will go up.Also, in the corporate version, both Walmart and the fake targe=
t company will deny the story. In the crypto version, Walmart will probably=
 be confused, and it=E2=80=99s not even clear what it would mean for a cryp=
tocurrency to deny a statement. A cryptocurrency is decentralized, etc.; th=
ere is not necessarily anyone who makes decisions for it and can say =E2=80=
=9Cthis is fake.=E2=80=9D Though in this particular case there is someone w=
ho controls the @litecoin Twitter account and  confirmed the fake press rel=
ease, ahahahaha:A significant spike in Litecoin followed quickly-debunked h=
eadlines that Walmart Inc., the world=E2=80=99s largest retailer, had agree=
d to accept the cryptocurrency as a payment mechanism at its stores. Liteco=
in=E2=80=99s own verified Twitter account posted a link to the press releas=
e in a tweet that was later deleted. Charlie Lee, creator of Litecoin and m=
anaging director of the Litecoin Foundation, described the tweet and press =
release as an =E2=80=9Cunfortunate situation=E2=80=9D in an interview with =
Bloomberg News.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe @litecoin handle, we have three people wh=
o control that and one of the people this morning, before I woke up, saw th=
e GlobeNewswire [press release] and saw Yahoo News posting it and CNBC post=
ing it and he thought it was true because he didn=E2=80=99t know better,=E2=
=80=9D Lee said. =E2=80=9CPretty soon after that he realized he had made a =
mistake, that it was fake and he deleted it.=E2=80=9DI love it. If you run =
social media=C2=A0at Amalgamated Widgets and you see a press release on the=
 news saying =E2=80=9CWalmart has bought Amalgamated Widgets,=E2=80=9D you =
are going to ask your boss =E2=80=9Cis this true=E2=80=9D before tweeting a=
bout it; that=E2=80=99s the sort of thing you might expect to hear from you=
r own company. If you run social media for Litecoin just wave it all in, wh=
o knows, what does truth even mean.Good times, good times. One assumes that=
 this is illegal =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely it=E2=80=99s wire fraud? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and that U.S. authorities will be looking for whoever did it; this is=
 just too fun a fraud not to prosecute. I do wonder if the=C2=A0SEC=C2=A0wi=
ll go after this person (if they can find them) for=C2=A0securities=C2=A0fr=
aud.[1] It=E2=80=99s not really securities fraud; Litecoin is not a securit=
y. But=C2=A0Walmart=C2=A0is, and its stock moved on the news. If you accide=
ntally manipulated Walmart=E2=80=99s stock as part of your cunning plan to =
manipulate Litecoin, that might be enough for the SEC.
