      What=E2=80=99s Gary Gensler up to?
   =20
 =20
This sort of resists summarization, but today U.S. Securities and Exchange =
Commission Chair[3] Gary Gensler has both prepared congressional testimony =
and an interview with Jen Wieczner at New York Magazine about what he=E2=80=
=99s up to at the SEC. Not like =E2=80=9Chere's a particular thing that I=
=E2=80=99m passionate about and my plan for new rulemaking,=E2=80=9D but mo=
re like =E2=80=9Chere is everything I=E2=80=99m thinking about with one sen=
tence on each thing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0If I had to give a broad summary, =
I guess I would go with =E2=80=9Cmore disclosure=E2=80=9D? That is a boring=
 summary; pretty much every speech and interview given by every SEC chair s=
ince the founding of the agency could probably be summarized that way. None=
theless I think it=E2=80=99s accurate. From the testimony:The security-base=
d swaps market is not a large market compared to the fixed income and equit=
y markets, but it was at the core of the 2008 financial crisis. More recent=
ly, total return swaps were at the heart of the failure of Archegos Capital=
 Management, a family office. =E2=80=A6.=C2=A0To allow the Commission and t=
he public to see aggregate positions, Congress under Exchange Act Section 1=
0B gave us authority to mandate disclosure for positions in security-based =
swaps and related securities. I=E2=80=99ve asked staff to think about poten=
tial rules for the Commission=E2=80=99s consideration under this authority.=
 As the collapse of Archegos showed, this may be an important reform to con=
siderToday=E2=80=99s investors are looking for consistent, comparable, and =
decision-useful disclosures around climate risk, human capital, and cyberse=
curity. I=E2=80=99ve asked staff to develop proposals for the Commission=E2=
=80=99s consideration on these potential disclosures. =E2=80=A6First, given=
 the surge in special purpose acquisition companies (SPACs), I have asked s=
taff for recommendations about enhancing disclosures in these investments. =
=E2=80=A6Further, we are working to enhance disclosures with regard to how =
Chinese companies issue securities in the U.S. Chinese companies conducting=
 business in certain industries, such as internet and technology, are prohi=
bited from selling their ownership stake to foreigners. =E2=80=A6We=E2=80=
=99ve seen a growing number of funds market themselves as =E2=80=9Cgreen,=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Csustainable,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Clow-carbon,=E2=80=9D and =
so on. I=E2=80=99ve asked staff to consider ways to determine what informat=
ion stands behind those claims and how we can ensure that the public has th=
e information they need to understand their investment choices among these =
types of funds.=C2=A0The SEC is so pleasing because it is simultaneously th=
e U.S.=E2=80=99s  most general-purpose=C2=A0regulatory agency, the one that=
 can move fast and aggressively to address climate change and Chinese geopo=
litics and financial stability, but it is also the most single-tool=C2=A0re=
gulatory agency, in that it addresses all of these issues by mandating more=
 disclosure.=C2=A0Three more specific points. First, Gensler continues to b=
e a skeptic of modern equity market structure. From his interview with Wiec=
zner:The orders that we put in on a digital app by and large don=E2=80=99t =
go to stock ex-changes like NASDAQ and NYSE. They go to wholesalers; some p=
eople just call it the =E2=80=9Cdark pools.=E2=80=9D And so a lot of our ma=
rkets are not lit. We don=E2=80=99t have that order competition that can dr=
ive efficiency in a market. There=E2=80=99s somebody paying for the order f=
low. That=E2=80=99s not necessarily the best flow for us. =E2=80=A6Can I ju=
st say something? It=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=9Cfree.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a m=
isnomer. It is not free, and it costs everybody who goes on those platforms=
. Because the platform is doing multiple things: One, they=E2=80=99re selli=
ng your order flow. Two, they=E2=80=99re collecting data, and the person pa=
ying for the order flow is getting that data. There=E2=80=99s an inherent c=
onflict because your order =E2=80=94 your buy or sell order =E2=80=94 is no=
t necessarily competing in the market. So it is anything but free.I don=E2=
=80=99t know! We've talked a bit around here about the notion of banning pa=
yment for order flow, but Gensler=E2=80=99s personal preference seems to be=
 to go further than I thought plausible and ban all sorts of =E2=80=9Cdark=
=E2=80=9D trading, forcing everyone to trade on an exchange. I would not be=
t on that happening, nor do I think it=E2=80=99s a good idea, but it keeps =
coming up.Second, Gensler really doesn=E2=80=99t like crypto. From his test=
imony:Right now, large parts of the field of crypto are sitting astride of =
=E2=80=94 not operating within =E2=80=94 regulatory frameworks that protect=
 investors and consumers, guard against illicit activity, and ensure for fi=
nancial stability.Currently, we just don=E2=80=99t have enough investor pro=
tection in crypto finance, issuance, trading, or lending. Frankly, at this =
time, it=E2=80=99s more like the Wild West or the old world of =E2=80=9Cbuy=
er beware=E2=80=9D that existed before the securities laws were enacted. Th=
is asset class is rife with fraud, scams, and abuse in certain applications=
. We can do better.And from the interview:=C2=A0I think that registration i=
s a way to bring a lot of the market into the public-policy framework, into=
 the investor-protection framework, the anti-money-laundering and tax-compl=
iance framework. ...Jay Clayton said it pretty well in February 2018 in con=
gressional testimony =E2=80=94 that he hadn=E2=80=99t seen a token yet that=
 didn=E2=80=99t pass the Howey Test. In 1933, Congress included a definitio=
n of security that was pretty inclusive, and the Supreme Court has reaffirm=
ed it multiple times. You exchange money with some common enterprise, and y=
ou=E2=80=99re anticipating profit based upon the efforts of that common ent=
erprise.There=E2=80=99s been about 5,000 initial coin offerings or projects=
. Some of them failed; some of them were frauds and fake. About 75 or 80 pu=
rportedly have market caps over $1 billion. And this is a $2.1 trillion glo=
bal asset class. I think it=E2=80=99s of a size that we need to address, an=
d seriously address. Anything that we do to bring more investor protection =
to this Wild West of the crypto market, I think, has benefits.As Wieczner w=
rites, =E2=80=9CGensler is a traditionalist in the sense that he believes t=
he laws currently governing the market, which date back to the Great Depres=
sion, are sufficient to handle modern inventions like bitcoin.=E2=80=9D I t=
hink a lot of crypto people would disagree with that, but it=E2=80=99s obvi=
ously the SEC=E2=80=99s position.Finally, people are worried about bond mar=
ket liquidity:Following the challenges of the spring of 2020, I believe we =
can build greater resiliency in both money market funds and open-end bond f=
unds. I=E2=80=99ve asked staff for recommendations to address those issues,=
 building upon feedback we received on the President=E2=80=99s Working Grou=
p report as well as other information. =E2=80=A6Given significant growth in=
 open-end funds and some lessons learned last spring, I believe it also is =
appropriate to take a close look at this $5-plus trillion sector, to enhanc=
e resiliency during periods of stress.You don=E2=80=99t hear so much anymor=
e about the =E2=80=9Cillusion of liquidity=E2=80=9D created by bond mutual =
funds, which in periods of stress might face redemptions, dump their bonds =
and lead to a worsening fire sale. But it=E2=80=99s on the SEC=E2=80=99s ra=
dar.
