   =20
      Briefcases
   =20
 =20
Here at Money Stuff we always enjoy a good  euphemism for =E2=80=9Cbribes,=
=E2=80=9D but I confess this one =E2=80=94=C2=A0which seems to be pretty st=
andard? =E2=80=94=C2=A0was new to me:One aspect is the role of intermediari=
es, often favored by governments in the region. The so-called briefcase com=
panies act as conduits for traders=E2=80=99 bribes to officials, taking a c=
ut and directing state business back to the traders. Glencore was a dominan=
t player in Nigeria, Chad, the Republic of Congo and Equatorial Guinea, and=
 says it no longer uses intermediaries as part of a revamped and cleaned-up=
 operation. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CAn issue that comes up with trader corruption is=
 agents and intermediaries in the mix,=E2=80=9D said Alexandra Gillies, an =
adviser at the Natural Resource Governance Institute, which seeks to stamp =
out corruption in emerging market resources. =E2=80=9CClearly it=E2=80=99s =
the top modus operandi for how these schemes work.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It is from=
 a story about a Glencore Plc oil trader who confessed to paying bribes, th=
rough intermediaries, to African government officials. If you just wire mon=
ey to a government official, that is a bribe and it=E2=80=99s pretty obviou=
s. But if you wire money to a well-connected local consulting firm, you are=
 paying reasonable consulting fees for an expert with local knowledge who c=
an give you guidance on how to win deals legitimately. And if the consultin=
g firm keeps 10% of the fee for itself and stuffs the rest in a briefcase t=
o hand to a government official, well, how were you supposed to know?=C2=A0
