<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG: Bar charts</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25040090.270564/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDgvc29tZW9uZS1pcy1nb2luZy10by1kcmlsbC10=
aGUtb2ls/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbd32ee79" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said before</a> that there are <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25040090.270564/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTMvZWxvbi1tdXNr=
LW5ldmVyLXdhbnRlZC10by1iZS10ZXNsYS1jZW8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc566fa13" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> two basic=
 theories</a> of environmental, social and governance investing. One says =
=E2=80=9Cwe will avoid investing in companies that do bad things, which wil=
l drive up their cost of capital, which will lead to a reduction in the num=
ber of bad things in the world.=E2=80=9D This has the advantage of (purport=
edly)=C2=A0<em>doing good in the world:=C2=A0</em>There is some mechanism b=
y which your investing choices reduce pollution, solve=C2=A0climate change,=
 etc. It has the disadvantage of=C2=A0<em>foregoing returns:=C2=A0</em>If y=
ou are raising the cost of capital of bad things, that means that the bad t=
hings have a higher return, and someone else is getting that return.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other theory says =E2=80=9Cwe will avoid comp=
anies that do bad things, because doing bad things is unsustainable, and ev=
entually the companies that do bad things will all go bankrupt.=E2=80=9D Th=
is has the advantage of promising higher returns: If you choose stocks that=
 will go up, and avoid the stocks that go bankrupt, that=E2=80=99s good for=
 your investors. It makes no particular do-gooder claims, though. You=E2=80=
=99re not making any claims about changing the world; you are just trying t=
o make money from your prediction about how the world will change anyway.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third theory would be =E2=80=9Cwe will inv=
est in companies that do bad things[2] and turn them into companies that do=
 good things, because (1) that is good and (2) doing bad things is unsustai=
nable and eventually companies that continue to do bad things will go bankr=
upt.=E2=80=9D This has the advantage of promising higher returns (through s=
top-doing-bad-things activism)=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>of doing good in the =
world. It is a nice synergy of the two approaches; you are claiming both to=
 have a direct positive impact on the world and to outperform the market.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This third theory is, I think, hard for the =
average ESG fund to pull off. If you are buying 0.1% of a handful of compan=
