bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> most general-<em>purpose</em>=C2=A0regulatory agency</a>, the one that ca=
n move fast and aggressively to address climate change and Chinese geopolit=
ics and financial stability, but it is also the most single-<em>tool=C2=A0<=
/em>regulatory agency, in that it addresses all of these issues by mandatin=
g more disclosure.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three more specifi=
c points. First, Gensler continues to be a skeptic of modern equity market =
structure. From his interview with Wieczner:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">The orders that we put in on a digital app by and large don=
=E2=80=99t go to stock ex-changes like NASDAQ and NYSE. They go to wholesal=
ers; some people just call it the =E2=80=9Cdark pools.=E2=80=9D And so a lo=
t of our markets are not lit. We don=E2=80=99t have that order competition =
that can drive efficiency in a market. There=E2=80=99s somebody paying for =
the order flow. That=E2=80=99s not necessarily the best flow for us. =E2=80=
=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Can I just say something? It=E2=80=99s =
not =E2=80=9Cfree.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a misnomer. It is not free, and it=
 costs everybody who goes on those platforms. Because the platform is doing=
 multiple things: One, they=E2=80=99re selling your order flow. Two, they=
=E2=80=99re collecting data, and the person paying for the order flow is ge=
tting that data. There=E2=80=99s an inherent conflict because your order =
=E2=80=94 your buy or sell order =E2=80=94 is not necessarily competing in =
the market. So it is anything but free.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! We've talked a bit around here about the no=
tion of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25040090.2=
70564/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDgtM=
zEvd2hhdC1oYXBwZW5zLXRvLXJvYmluaG9vZC1pZi10aGUtc2VjLWJhbnMtcGF5bWVudC1mb3It=
b3JkZXItZmxvdy1rdDBhNWtqZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa21978a1" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">banning payment for ord=
er flow</a>, but Gensler=E2=80=99s personal preference seems to be to go fu=
rther than I thought plausible and ban all sorts of =E2=80=9Cdark=E2=80=9D =
trading, forcing everyone to trade on an exchange. I would not bet on that =
<em>happening</em>, nor do I think it=E2=80=99s a good idea, but it keeps c=
oming up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, Gensler really doesn=E2=
=80=99t like crypto. From his testimony:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Right now, large parts of the field of crypto are sitting astride=
 of =E2=80=94 not operating within =E2=80=94 regulatory frameworks that pro=
tect investors and consumers, guard against illicit activity, and ensure fo=
r financial stability.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Currently, we just d=
on=E2=80=99t have enough investor protection in crypto finance, issuance, t=
rading, or lending. Frankly, at this time, it=E2=80=99s more like the Wild =
West or the old world of =E2=80=9Cbuyer beware=E2=80=9D that existed before=
 the securities laws were enacted. This asset class is rife with fraud, sca=
ms, and abuse in certain applications. We can do better.</p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And from the interview:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that registration is a way to bring a lot=
 of the market into the public-policy framework, into the investor-protecti=
on framework, the anti-money-laundering and tax-compliance framework. ...</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jay Clayton said it pretty well in February =
2018 in congressional testimony =E2=80=94 that he hadn=E2=80=99t seen a tok=
en yet that didn=E2=80=99t pass the Howey Test. In 1933, Congress included =
a definition of security that was pretty inclusive, and the Supreme Court h=
as reaffirmed it multiple times. You exchange money with some common enterp=
rise, and you=E2=80=99re anticipating profit based upon the efforts of that=
 common enterprise.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s been ab=
out 5,000 initial coin offerings or projects. Some of them failed; some of =
them were frauds and fake. About 75 or 80 purportedly have market caps over=
 $1 billion. And this is a $2.1 trillion global asset class. I think it=E2=
=80=99s of a size that we need to address, and seriously address. Anything =
that we do to bring more investor protection to this Wild West of the crypt=
o market, I think, has benefits.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">As Wieczner writes, =E2=80=9CGensler is a traditionalist in the sense th=
at he believes the laws currently governing the market, which date back to =
the Great Depression, are sufficient to handle modern inventions like bitco=
in.=E2=80=9D I think a lot of crypto people would disagree with that, but i=
t=E2=80=99s obviously the SEC=E2=80=99s position.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Finally, people are worried about bond market liquidity:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Following the challenges of the spring of =
2020, I believe we can build greater resiliency in both money market funds =
and open-end bond funds. I=E2=80=99ve asked staff for recommendations to ad=
dress those issues, building upon feedback we received on the President=E2=
=80=99s Working Group report as well as other information. =E2=80=A6</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given significant growth in open-end funds and so=
me lessons learned last spring, I believe it also is appropriate to take a =
close look at this $5-plus trillion sector, to enhance resiliency during pe=
riods of stress.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You don=E2=80=
=99t hear so much anymore about the =E2=80=9Cillusion of liquidity=E2=80=9D=
 created by bond mutual funds, which in periods of stress might face redemp=
tions, dump their bonds and lead to a worsening fire sale. But it=E2=80=99s=
 on the SEC=E2=80=99s radar.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" bord=
er=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
